Altech, Capitec, Massmart, Omnia Could Move: South African Stocks Preview

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-09-27T23:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-27/altech-capitec-massmart-omnia-south-african-equity-preview.html
The following stocks may rise or
fall in  South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last close.  The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index rose the most in 16
months, advancing 1,033.84, or 3.5 percent, to 30,752.40 by the
5 p.m. close in Johannesburg, its first gain in five days.  Allied Technologies Ltd. (ALT)  : The maker of television
set-top boxes releases results for the year to Aug. 31. Earnings
per share fell as much as 25 percent, the company said in a
trading statement on Sept. 19. Shares in the company fell 1.7
percent to 58.02 rand.  Capitec Bank Holdings Ltd. (CPI)  : South Africa’s
fastest-growing bank announces results for the six months
through August. Earnings per share rose at least 45 percent, the
company said in a trading statement on Aug. 16. The stock added
1.2 percent to 186 rand.  Massmart Holdings Ltd. (MSM)  : The South African retailer
controlled by Wal-Mart Stores Inc. holds a general meeting of
shareholders. Shares in the retailer added 1.9 percent to 148
rand.  Nedbank Group Ltd. (NED)  : Nedbank  Namibia , a unit of
South Africa’s fourth biggest bank, said net income fell 19
percent to 48.3 million Namibian dollars ($6.2 million) during
the six months to June 30. Shares in Nedbank gained 5 percent to
138.55 rand.  Omnia Holdings Ltd. (OMN)  : the company, which produces
and distributes fertilizers and explosives, holds its annual
general meeting. The stock gained 0.4 percent to 75.79 rand.  Sanlam Group Ltd. (SLM SJ): The largest South Africa-based
Insurer said Armien Tyer, the head of its asset management unit,
left and will be replaced by Cora Fernandez, head of Sanlam
Private Equity. Shares in the company rose 3.7 percent to 27.06
rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
